      "createdAt": "2026-03-22T20:35:43.658742+00:00",
      "role": "assistant",
      "contents": [
        {
          "$type": "text",
          "text": "Priya, it's great that you're paying attention to how your body is responding to training — that kind of self-awareness is genuinely one of your strengths as a runner. Long run fatigue and light-headedness are worth taking seriously, and I'm glad you're asking rather than just pushing through.\n\nBefore I share anything on the fueling side, I want to be straightforward with you about where my expertise ends.\n\n---\n\n**On the iron supplements and light-headedness:** That's a medical question, and I'd be doing you a disservice if I weighed in on it. Light-headedness after runs can have several different causes, and iron is just one possibility — and supplementing without knowing your actual levels can cause harm. I'd really encourage you to see your GP and ask for a blood panel, including ferritin and hemoglobin. That's the only way to know what's actually going on. Once you have that information, it'll also help us make smarter training decisions together.\n\n**On the meal plan:** That's outside my scope too — I'm not a registered dietitian, and I wouldn't want to give you something that looks authoritative but isn't tailored to your full picture. A sports dietitian would be genuinely worth the investment at this stage of marathon prep.\n\n---\n\n**On the keto idea — here's where I can help.** Would it be okay if I shared what the research and practice generally shows about fat adaptation and marathon training? I want to give you the full picture, not just a yes or no.\n\nWhat I can say is that the light-headedness and energy dips you're describing on long runs are *really* common at your training load — and there are fueling *timing* strategies (not a diet plan, just when and what category of fuel around runs) that fall squarely in my lane as a coach. Those often make a meaningful difference before any dietary overhaul.\n\n---\n\nLooking at your recent training, you've been doing some genuinely solid work — that 26 km long run at 5:34/km and the marathon pace session the day before show real fitness and commitment. That's not nothing.\n\nCan I ask: **what does your fueling look like on a typical long run day — before, during, and after?** That'll help me understand what we're actually working with."
        }
      ],
